On the other hand, referring to the negative comments: if you are a picky eater, and currently facing a "COVID-19 phobia" or are accustomed to eating out just at high end restaurants, and if you're a Karen. This place is a gold mine, it's amazing, the best food in the Bronx, what more can I say.  1st let me say if you are from out of town or from a good part of NYC and can't handle food being handled with no gloves, or no mask, or running water, please do yourself a favor and stay away, this place is not for you.  If you're used to eating on the side of a dirt road in another country then by all means pull up a chair.  I got here around 11:30 on a foggy Saturday morning,.  The Lechon (pig) wasn't going to be ready for about another 1/2 and hour, so while I waited he offered his pastelitos that came out fresh from the frier.   Piraña will talk to a dead man, so having a conversation was fun.  Finally it was time and boy it didn't disappoint, the skin was crispy and pork juicy, I had a mofongo de camarón and that was absolutely amazing, he ceviche de pulpo was on another level, this man will literally give you food without asking for money if need be, so for all that I humbly gave him 50 bucks (I don't even know prices so I can't review it).  This was an experience like no other and I recommend you  try it before it's gone.  As for some Concon he'll gladly give it to you free of charge, and if you want to stand out buy him a Heineken and thank me later.  Enjoy and stay safe

This is an experience, not food. My mom and I drove from Dallas, TX to NYC during covid and risked it all for this place. We were first in line at 11:30 and didn't leave until 2:30. Not because there was a wait but because you get immersed with the locals, music, and Angel himself. Taking a trip here felt like we arrive in Puerto Rico without a plane ticket. The best way I can describe the flavor is to rearrange carbon molecules from a pencil lead and change it to a diamond. I've had this food before, these same ingredients but it literally made my heart race and hug my mom with joy. I can't say enough other than forget what you think you know about the Bronx and come visit. You'll be treated like the favorite cousin, like a winning lottery ticket, and the ice cold beer in the desert. Thank-You Piriana for you have extended my life here on Earth with your food.

My friend and I came in from Manhattan to visit Angel's Puerto Rican food truck in the South Bronx.  Suffice to say that going to Lechonera La Piraña is not like a typical Manhattan Halal cart, it's more of an "immersive" experience because he welcomes you into his food truck, both literally (you climb up a rickety black metal staircase to enter into the truck) and figuratively (he treats his customers like family).  He clearly has a bit of a following, because even on a cold winter day he had a small line of people... but luckily we didn't have to wait long before we were welcomed inside. I was a bit intimated as I didn't know the ordering protocol but Angel put me at ease, behind the counter, expertly cutting up pork with a large machete...  He quickly offered us a sample of the pork and also a little plastic cups of his split pea soup which was delicious. Maybe we looked like out-of-towners because he asked us how we heard about him and we told him about the Vice article and he said that people come from all over to try his lechón.  He delivered heaping piles of food to us in take-out containers.  Angel himself, as well as other people leaned in to take photos of our food 'cuz it looked so tasty and the other guests said they had already eaten their food and wanted photos.  Note that Portion sizes were EXTREMELY large.  There was a tasty garlic sauce and also hot sauces available.  One was a home-made Puerto Rican hot sauce in an orange juice container that was very tasty.  My friend ordered shrimp sauce over rice + pork on the side.  I ordered just the pork.  I asked for salad but he didn't have any so I got only pork.  He did not have soda.  We paid $27.00 for everything.  Would go back again in the future.
